<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911224-0131</DOCNO><DOCID>911224-0131.</DOCID><HL>   Vista Chemical Co.   Ex-Analyst Agrees   To Pay SEC Fine   ----   By Sandra Block   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>12/24/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C5</SO><CO>   G.RWE</CO><MS>BASIC MATERIALS (BSC)</MS><IN>CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)</IN><NS>INSIDER TRADING (ISD)STOCK andamp; OTHER MARKET NEWS (STK)</NS><GV>SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)</GV><RE>EUROPE (EU)GERMANY (GE)NORTH AMERICA (NME)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Securities and Exchange Commissioncharged a former financial analyst for Vista Chemical Co. andhis brother with insider trading in connection with a Germancompany's 1990 acquisition of the U.S. concern.   The SEC said Thomas Roberts, a former senior financialanalyst with Vista Chemical, and his brother, WilliamRoberts, earned $48,691 in illegal profits by buying Vistacommon stock and options before the $590 million deal wasannounced with the unit of RWE AG, a German industrialconcern.</LP><TEXT>   Without admitting or denying the allegations, ThomasRoberts agreed to pay $20,253 in fines and trading profits,while William Roberts agreed to pay $38,565 representing histrading profits.   The SEC said Thomas Roberts, who left Houston-based VistaChemical in April, learned of the proposed acquisition in May1990 when a supervisor asked him to prepare financial reportsabout the deal. From June to September 1990, Thomas Robertspurchased 435 shares of Vista stock, the SEC said, nettingprofits of $10,126.   The SEC alleged that Thomas Roberts told his brotherWilliam about the proposed acquisition in June 1990. DuringAugust and September of that year, William Roberts purchased29 Vista call option contracts, netting profits of $38,565,the SEC said.   An attorney for Thomas Roberts said the case involved a&quot;rather small stock purchase.&quot; The attorney said Mr. Robertswanted to put the matter behind him. An attorney for WilliamRoberts also noted that the case against his client involveda small number of trades. &quot;This isn't the clearest area ofthe law but you just don't litigate with the government overthis amount of money,&quot; he said.   The SEC said its investigation of the case is continuing.</TEXT></DOC>